
[1]rapacious

   RAPA'CIOUS, a. [L. rapax, from rapio, to seize. See Rap.]

   1. Given to plunder; disposed or accustomed to seize by violence;
   seizing by force; as a rapacious enemy.

   Well may thy lord, appeas'd redeem thee quite from death's rapacious
   claim.

   2. Accustomed to seize for food; subsisting on prey or animals seized
   by violence; as a rapacious tiger; a rapacious fowl.
